@realDonaldTrump Trump is on roll. After threatening to withhold funds from WHO, Trump threatened to adjourn Congress so that he could make “recess appointments.” He has lost his mind; there is no other explanation. Let me explain. Most presidential appointments of “senior

officers” must be confirmed by the Senate. When the Senate is slow to act, or refuses to confirm a nominee, presidents can resort to a temporary “recess appointment” when the Senate is not in session. Since the Senate views “recess appointments” as an end-run around its

constitutional role of providing “advice and consent” regarding nominations, it goes to great lengths to avoid “adjourning”—i.e., going into recess. It does so by opening a Senate session for a few minutes each day, then closing the session without conducting any business.

The Senate has been doing so since it passed the CARES Act in March. Trump loves recess appointments because it allows him to shuffle lackeys in-and-out of government without pesky oversight by the Senate. Trump desperately wants to appoint a new Director of the Voice of America—

which Trump believes is saying bad (truthful) things about Trump.” But Trump can’t make a recess appointment because the Senate will not adjourn. So, Trump has threatened to adjourn Congress so he can make recess appointments. Here’s the problem. The president cannot willy-nilly

adjourn Congress. He can do so only if Congress is deadlocked about when to adjourn. No such deadlock exists, and Trump’s attempt to adjourn Congress would be without constitutional authority. See Forbes, “Trump Threatens To Adjourn Congress But Constitutional Law Expert Says

He’s Misinterpreting His Power.” Indeed, Congress has already set a date for adjournment—January 3, 2021. McConnell could try to change that date, thereby creating a disagreement with the House, but he would need to eliminate the filibuster rule. Not likely to happen.

appearance that he was “listening” to health experts and business leaders to help him decide when to reopen. Hogwash. Trump’s medical experts continue to advise that the country will not be ready to reopen on May 1st. Trump was unable to convince any business leaders to join his

“Opening Our Country Council,” so he unilaterally released a list of business leaders whom he can blame if the pandemic re-ignites after May 1st. To help spread the blame, Trump held a series of conference calls on Wednesday with dozens of hapless victims organized under the

preposterous name of “The Great American Economic Revival Industry Groups.” In my house, we would refer to a similar event as a “Zoom call.” In Trump’s mind, the coronavirus is irrelevant to his decision to reopen the country. The coronavirus will prove otherwise. Having become

a pandemic, it will remain so until we contain it by active measures. Trump’s excessive pride and unwarranted confidence amount to hubris—but we will be the victims of his nemesis, the coronavirus. Trump’s premature declaration of victory has already caused the most unstable
